Autocall structured products: a case study of Vale S.A. (PDF Download Available)









For full functionality of ResearchGate it is necessary to enable JavaScript.
            Here are the 
                instructions how to enable JavaScript in your web browser.








See all ›22 ReferencesSee all ›4 FiguresDownload citationShare Facebook  Twitter  Google+  LinkedIn  Reddit Download full-text PDF 


 

Autocall structured products: a case study of Vale S.A.Article · January 2012 with 576 ReadsDOI: 10.1504/IJFMD.2012.053343 Cite this publication1st Paulo Vitor Jordão da Gama Silva3.23 · Federal Rural University of Rio de Janeiro2nd Antônio Carlos Figueiredo Pinto15.34 · Pontifícia Universidade Católica do Rio de Janeiro3rd Marcelo Klotzle14.77 · Pontifícia Universidade Católica do Rio de JaneiroAbstractThis article analyses the pricing, using autocall mechanisms, of a coupon barrier note issue based on ADRs of Brazil's biggest mining and metals company: Vale S.A. (VALE). The numerical method used was based on a modification of the trinomial tree model with auto-call, barrier and knock-in conditions, and which was modified to calculate present value. This model was shown to be practical and agile for processing the database and handling considerably volatile scenarios and was also validated by the product's actual behaviour, revealing that the product was not financially attractive for maintaining an autocall operation strategy (achieve a gain with the product maturing in the short term and switch to similar products). The aim of this article is to show a new pricing method involving autocall structured products with functioning typologies similar to those of the issue analysed in the present study.Discover the world's research13+ million members100+ million publications700k+ research projectsJoin for free4 Figures




                 Int. J. Financial Markets and Derivatives, Vol. 3, No. 1, 2012  71      Copyright © 2012 Inderscience Enterprises Ltd.                     Autocall structured products: a case study of  Vale S.A. Paulo Vitor Jordão da Gama Silva*,  Antonio Carlos Figueiredo Pinto and  Marcelo Cabus Klotzle Department of Administration IMA (Institute of Management and Administration), Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro (PUC-RJ), Rua Marquês de São Vicente, 225, Gávea – Rio de Janeiro, RJ – 22451 – 900 Brazil E-mail: rjdagama@ig.com.br E-mail: figueiredo@iag.puc-rio.br E-mail: klotzle@iag.puc-rio.br *Corresponding author Abstract: This article analyses the pricing, using autocall mechanisms, of a coupon barrier note issue based on ADRs of Brazil’s biggest mining and metals company: Vale S.A. (VALE). The numerical method used was based on a modification of the trinomial tree model with auto-call, barrier and knock-in conditions, and which was modified to calculate present value. This model was shown to be practical and agile for processing the database and handling considerably volatile scenarios and was also validated by the product’s actual behaviour, revealing that the product was not financially attractive for maintaining an autocall operation strategy (achieve a gain with the product maturing in the short term and switch to similar products). The aim of this article is to show a new pricing method involving autocall structured products with functioning typologies similar to those of the issue analysed in the present study. Keywords: financial derivatives; structured products; autocall; Vale S.A.; VALE; modified trinomial tree; finite difference method. Reference to this paper should be made as follows: da Gama Silva, P.V.J., Figueiredo Pinto, A.C. and Klotzle, M.C. (2012) ‘Autocall structured products: a case study of Vale S.A.’, Int. J. Financial Markets and Derivatives, Vol. 3, No. 1, pp.71–90. Biographical notes: Paulo Vitor Jordão da Gama Silva obtained a degree in Business Administration from the Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro (2010). He has a Master’s in Business Administration with an emphasis on finance at the same university (2013). Antônio Carlos Figueiredo Pinto obtained a degree in Administration from the Rio de Janeiro State University (1977). He has a PhD in Economics from the EPGE of the Getulio Vargas Foundation – RJ (1985) He is currently a Professor at the Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro. He has published various articles in the field of administration, with an emphasis on derivatives, financial markets and portfolio management. He has published books and articles in Brazil and abroad. 


                 72  P.V.J. da Gama Silva et al.                            Marcelo Cabus Klotzle holds a degree in Administration – University of Bayreuth (1993), a Master’s degree in Administration – Universityof Bayreuth (1994) and a PhD in Economics – Catholic University of Eichstätt (1999). He obtained a Postdoctoral degree in Behavioral Finance from McMaster University (2009). He is currently a Professor at the Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro. He has a wide experience in the administration and economics areas, with an emphasis on financial administration, capital markets and international economics and finance, and is mainly engaged with the following themes: corporate governance, behavioural finance, capital markets, econometrics, international finance and the international economy. He has published books and articles in Brazil and abroad.  1 Introduction In recent years, retail and high net income investors all over the world have been seeking new investment opportunities that offer attractive returns and therefore considering products that differ from traditional investments (although not necessarily seeking full principal protection). Thus, products that enhance these yields (such as autocall products) have become increasingly popular with investors. According to Deng et al. (2011), there has been a sharp increase in their use, with 40% annual growth recorded between 2007 and 2010. More than 2,500 autocall products were issued during the first six months of 2010. According to Baule et al. (2008), Bergstresser (2008), Deng et al. (2010) and Henderson and Pearson (2011) one of the reasons for this increase in autocall products is the ease with which they can be indexed to the products, acting essentially as a  market-linked investment that faces ‘forced redemption’ before the scheduled  maturity date if certain pre-determined market conditions are achieved. Drawing on Georgieva’s (2005) considerations regarding structured products and adapting these ideas to autocall dynamics, one may add a few more benefits of using this tool, such as: using it to hedge at a minimum or maximum level when hedging instruments are not available in the short-term market; take on risk judiciously in order to obtain higher returns; diversify in order to manage risk (in the case of autocall with more than one asset); avoid problems with potential market impact due to significant changes in asset allocation, amongst others. An autocall event occurs on pre-determined dates (which can occur at annual, quarterly intervals, etc.), specific for each type of product that can mature on the autocall date. The latter may be continuous or discrete, as shown in Figure 1(a) and (b). In the case of a continuous autocall date the product can only be autocalled when it attains the barrier during its whole duration, whereas in the discrete case there are certain ‘autocall dates’ on which the product may or may not face ‘forced redemption’ depending on its position in relation to the barrier level (the latter is characteristic of the Vale S.A. product analysed, with its predetermined dates). The underlying reference index S0 can be linked to the price of stocks, a basket of stocks or funds, amongst others such that if it reaches price level ‘C’ the company exercises the option to purchase the product, which is then automatically redeemed with the investor receiving the pre-determined coupon (initially agreed upon by contract) along with the principal invested. 


                  Autocall structured products  73                            Figure 1 Autocall in continuous and discrete periods, (a) continuous autocall (b) discrete autocall (see online version for colours)  (a) (b) Source:  CitiFirst – Informações sobre Termos e Condições In Figure 1 examples, the products were subject to autocall before the maturity date. Most autocall products have a protection feature so that if the autocall trigger has not occurred before the scheduled maturity date, the capital is fully protected and the investor receives all interest due, provided the price is greater than or equal to the barrier level. However if S is below this level, investors will be fully exposed to downside of the market and may suffer heavy losses. Thus is important to necessary to understand that the autocall product necessarily includes a put option on the maturity date. It is also interesting to observe that the ‘small’ period of time that has elapsed since its creation has seen the development of several variations of the original autocall model such as performance autocall, crescendo autocall, escalator autocall, bonus autocall and the premium express, with all of them influenced by characteristic instruments used to calculate payments on coupon dates. This article is divided into six sections. After this introduction, Section 2 presents the model developed to analyse the pricing of the autocall product issued by Vale S.A., as well as a review of the literature aimed at gaining a deeper knowledge of autocall mechanisms; the third provides a detailed explanation of the study’s title; Section 4 presents the methodology used and important data; the Section 5 shows the empirical results obtained and Section 6 presents the study’s conclusions. 2 Theoretical references This section performs an in-depth analysis of themes related to the models used for the pricing of autocall structured products, which are the trinomial tree and finite difference models. It will also focus on autocall theory itself (encompassing the most common types and their forms of payment). 2.1  Trinomial tree model The trinomial tree was introduced for the first time by Boyle (1986) and explained in Hull (2006) and Haug (1998). It is seen as constituting an extension of the binomial approach from Cox et al. (1979), and is conceptually similar. According to the trinomial 


                 74  P.V.J. da Gama Silva et al.                            method, the underlying stock is modelled as a recombination tree where the price has three possible paths at each node: upwards, downwards or stable. For standard type options, where the number of steps increases, results converge rapidly and the binomial model is then preferred due to its simple implementation. However, in the case of exotic options, the trinomial model (or adaptations) shows more stable and precise results, independently of the size of the step. According to the trinomial method, the price of the underlying stock is modelled as a recombination tree, where the price has three possible paths at each node: upwards, downwards and a stable or middle one. These values are found by multiplying the value at the current node by the appropriate factor, where: 2Tueσ××Δ= (1) 21Tde uσ−× ×Δ== (2) 1m= (3) u = price x’ s multiplicative additive increase factor d = price x’s multiplicative additive decrease factor m = price x’s multiplicative stability factor. Figure 2 illustrates the dynamics of stock prices in the trinomial tree, using n = 4 steps (for the time). Figure 2  Demonstration of the trinomial model  Source:  Rouah andVainberg (2007) 


                  Autocall structured products  75                            In order to contain all possible price movements in a trinomial tree with n steps, one needs a matrix with 2n + 1 lines and n+ 1 columns, corresponding to a size 9 × 5 matrix. The increase, decrease and stability probabilities are represented (in this order) by the following formulas: ()22222TTrqTTeePueeσσσΔΔ−×−×ΔΔ×−×⎛⎞−⎜⎟=⎜⎟−⎝⎠ (4) ()22222TTrqTTeePdeeσσσΔΔ×−×ΔΔ×−×⎛⎞−⎜⎟=⎜⎟−⎝⎠ (5) ()1Pm Pu Pd=− +  (6) where Δ t is the period of time, ơ is the volatility adopted, r is the rate of interest paid, q represents dividend payments (which in this case would is zero), and Pu and Pd are unconditionally positive. The modification of the tree for the pricing of structured products with complex variables is introduced for the first time in this study and will be detailed later in the methodology as a model which seeks to simply the calculation by adopting a processing dynamic that is low in terms of computational capacity. It should be noted that this model was chosen because, according to Anderson et al. (1997), it is clear that implicit methods require additional computation skills and their implementation can be much more difficult. Implicit methods are used in problems where the use of an explicit method would require impracticably small steps to ensure limited errors. To attain the precision sought after in such problems, much less computational time is necessary than when using an implicit method. They are usually unconditionally stable and it is thus possible to use greater values in the steps so that a solution may be found more quickly. However, the computational cost also increases considerably which in turn increases the need for extensive database processing. A modelling that is similar to the trinomial model can be found in the explicit finite difference method which will be described below. 2.2  The finite difference model According to Collatz (1966), the finite difference model is a method for solving differential equations that is based on derivate approximation by finite differences. The formulas for finite differences can be obtained by developing Taylor series – see for example, Ames (1977), Roache (1976) and Lapidus and Piner (1982). The derived finite difference operator can be obtained from the Taylor series for the function:  ( ) () ()()'2xhxxhoh+= + +∫∫∫  Thus the derivative can be written as a difference plus an error term: 


                 76  P.V.J. da Gama Silva et al.                            () ()()()'xh xxohh+−=+∫∫∫ Ignoring the error term one obtains the finite difference operator for the first derivative f defined as:  () ()()xhxDx h+−=∫∫∫ (7) According to Vista (2010), regarding precision and order, the error in the solution of a method is defined as the difference between its approximation and the exact analytical solution. The two sources of error in finite difference methods are: the rounding error (which is the loss of precision due to computational rounding of decimal amounts – which can also occur in the trinomial model, jeopardising the results of very sensitive models and the truncation error (which is the residual that results when the exact solution of the dependent variable in the discretised equation of the mathematical model is substituted). In order to use a finite difference method to try to solve or usually obtain an approximate solution of a problem, one should first discretise the domination problem. This is usually performed by dividing the domination into a uniform grid, as can be seen in Figure 3. Figure 3 Discretisation of a function on a grid (see online version for colours)  Source:  Kaw and Kalu (2009) Note that this means that finite difference methods produce discrete sets of numerical approximations for the derivative (temporally in steps). The most common examples of this method are expressed in the form of ordinary differential equations and in the heat equation. In the approach of the model used by Deng et al. (2011) for the pricing of autocall products, the authors use an explicit calculation of finite differences and partial differential equations (PDE) with the Black-Scholes formula, as presented by Zvan et al. (2000) which discusses the PDE methodology for the pricing of barrier options. It is also worth mentioning that the Monte Carlo model is another option of numerical method for the valuation of structured products. 


                  Autocall structured products  77                            2.3 Autocall According to Fries and Joshi (2011) and Georgieva (2005), the use of autocall structure products has become common in recent years, also because they act similarly to a rational investor who has a broad view of the underlying asset. According to Deng et al. (2011), the fact that most structured products were of longer term (around five years or more) was regarded as a negative factor by many investors throughout the world. An interesting way of enhancing the reduction of an investment’s duration was discovered with the use of autocall products, which according to Alexander and Sheedy (2007) essentially function like a European barrier option, in which, if at a  pre-determined future date the market is above a defined trigger level, the structure will be automatically revoked, with investors receiving their principal along with a specified return. The eight-year period since the first autocall product was produced in 2003 has seen a series of innovations that have refined the original model, which according to Citifirst (2011) are: • Performance autocall: in which the auto-call coupon is not fixed at a specific level but pays the greater of X% and the actual underlying performance in the case of an auto-call event. • Crescendo autocall: in which the auto-call event depends on two underlyings being above the autocall barrier and besides this there is an additional condition in which the second underlying provides additional financing for higher autocall coupons. • Escalator autocall: in which the auto-call barrier decreases each year – increasing the likelihood of an autocall event and reducing the probability of capital at risk. • Bonus plus autocall: in which, besides the autocall coupon received at automatic maturity, investors receive a bonus coupon (in this case the earlier in the life of the product autocall occurs, the better) so that the effective per annum coupon is high in early years compared with a standard autocall note, thus reducing the value of coupon payments towards maturity. • Premium express: in which the autocall barrier is below 100% of the initial strike level aiming to provide a high autocall probability with full capital protection. Bouzoubaa and Osseiran (2010) perform a descriptive analysis of the main autocall structures considering: payments, performance and the dispersion effect itself (also considering hypothetical explanatory scenarios in order to better understand the analyses that follow below). 2.3.1  Unique assets subject to autocall 2.3.1.1 Payments description Considering a product with autocall based in one single asset S, the structure pays a coupon that depends basically on the underlying achieving trigger levels H and B, and whose payments are defined on each observation date ti, (i = 1...n), as follows:  


                 78  P.V.J. da Gama Silva et al.                            ()()() ()()ti tj0Ret B Max j 1, ,i 1 RetCoupon ti Invst C 1 1H⎡⎤⎡ ⎤≥=……− <⎢⎥⎣⎦⎣⎦=×× ×  (8) where Invst(0) is the initial investment C is the pre-determined coupon and Ret(ti) = S(ti) / S(0) is the return during period ti at the initial strike level S(0). If a wrapper1 strategy is applied to the note the investor will receive 100% of the Invst(0). In this case, however, the payment is not fixed. The Invst(0) can be redeemed on any observation date, not necessarily at the end of the product’s life: ()()() ()()0   1, , 1  11ti tjRet HMax j i Ret HRedemption ti Invst⎡⎤⎡ ⎤≥=……− <⎢⎥⎣⎦⎣⎦=× ×  (9) In the case of the payment described above, it is important to observe that the investor does not receive an additional payment if H is achieved on one of the observation dates. So a product is considered to have been auto-called if its life-cycle is interrupted when barrier H is achieved by the underlying on a specific observation date. The autocall structure itself does not have a fixed life-cycle until maturity. Maturity, in fact, is the maximum amount of time that a product manages to remain active. The autocall trigger (H) is a pre-determined level above which the autocall structure terminates and the investor receives the Invst(0) invested. Trigger i can be fixed during the life of the product or may vary. In some cases the trigger may also increase or decrease over time. The coupon trigger (B), also known as the coupon level, is a pre-determined level above which the investor receives a periodic coupon. In other words, if the underlying observation level is greater than the coupon trigger, a coupon based on the Invst(0) is paid to the investor. The autocall and coupon triggers of some structures involving autocall are equal and are known as autocall products with knock-out coupons. However, when the coupon is paid, the product is autocalled at the same time provided the autocall trigger has been attained. Thus, this structure pays a single coupon on an observation date during the whole life of the product. In cases in which the coupon level is different from the autocall trigger, the products are known as autocall products with knock-in coupons. 2.3.1.2 Payment mechanisms This section explains the various payment mechanisms through the simulation of scenarios, shown in Tables 1 and 2 accompanied by Figures 4 and 5, with a specific case to better understand the autocall structure. Consider a retail investor in an investment bank who invests US$ 5,000 in an autocall structured product based on the CAC 40 index with a three-year duration. Table 1  Payment scenarios for a structured product with autocall involving the CAC40 index   Scenario 1  Scenario 2  Scenario 3 Coupon in the end of the year 1  8.00%  8.00%  8.00% Coupon in the end of the year 2  8.00%  8.00%  0.00% Coupon in the end of the year 3 100.00% 108.00% 108.00% Source:  Bouzoubaa and Osseiran (2010, p.188) 


