hare under 100% (which is the autocall trigger), which produces a second coupon of 25%. At maturity, one of the shares has a performance of less than 60% (FORTIS). Therefore, there is no coupon at the end of the third year and the investor receives 100% of Invst(0) on this last observation date.  


                  Autocall structured products  81                            Figure 6  Return scenarios for underlying shares based on the worst performance of autocalls  Source  Bouzoubaa and Osseiran (2010, p.199) 2.3.2.2  The snowball effect and performance based on the worst of autocalls with put options tools When the autocall and coupon triggers are the same, the product terminates immediately after the payment of the coupon. In other words, only one coupon is paid. However, coupon payments can be modified, creating the so-called ‘snowball coupons’. If the product remains active until year i, this means that the investor has not received the periodic coupons. The ‘snowball’ structure allows the investor to receive a coupon equal to the sum of all previous coupons if the trigger is achieved. The performance based on the worst autocall can also be used as a down-and-in put option tool in the autocall structure. This occurs when an investor is willing to increase the potential coupon receipt and believes that the products that comprise the basket will act above a specific level. This means that the principal is no longer protected as the investor is in a short position in relation to a put option at the product’s redemption. As in the case of autocall products for a single asset, the put option can be a European option, underlying the basket of assets with the same expiry date as the final redemption date of the autocall. 2.3.2.3  Autocall of auto-performance Considering two assets S1 and S2, the auto-performance autocall which is based on the auto-performance of two assets S1 vs S2 typically functions like a European style option with coupon payments C on each observation date, in which S1 – S2 have a specific level of auto-performance called a cushion2. This auto-performance structure possesses an auto-call tool that pays a coupon on the early redemption. The product has payments on each observation date ti, as follows: ()()[]() ()()()()012  1, , 1 1  111Ret t