                 82  P.V.J. da Gama Silva et al.                            3  The Vale S.A. asset The Vale S.A. product is a structured note aimed at raising international funds (with a duration of at most a year), launched on the New York Stock Exchange with an autocall price of 100% of the initial price, coupon barrier set at 80% of the initial price and  knock-in level at 80% of the initial price. This product’s initial price was established on 03/04/2011, based on VALE’s closing price of U$ 34.50 (to two decimal points) taken from the Bloomberg database, which will mature on 04/02/2012. Thus the auto-call, coupon barrier and knock-in level prices are US$ 34.50, US$ 27.60 and US$ 27.60 respectively. The autocall validation dates are fixed monthly, as can be seen in Table 4. Table 4  Validation dates of the asset Autocall provision Valuation date  Mandatory early redemption date April 18, 2011   Valuation date + five business days May 18, 2011  Valuation date + five business days June 20, 2011  Valuation date + five business days July 18, 2011  Valuation date + five business days August 18, 2011  Valuation date + five business days September 19, 2011  Valuation date + five business days October 18, 2011  Valuation date + five business days November 18, 2011  Valuation date + five business days December 19, 2011  Valuation date + five business days January 18, 2012  Valuation date + five business days February 21, 2012  Valuation date + five business days March 19, 2012  Final valuation date Source: CitiFirst (2011) This issue pays 0.917% interest per month (approximately 11% a year) on the principal. If the price on the autocall date is equal to or greater than the autocall price, forced redemption occurs and investors receive their principal plus the respective month’s interest due, terminating the investment. If the product does not reach the autocall barrier and if it is above the coupon barrier and the knock-in level on the autocall date, interest is paid. When the price is below the autocall level and the coupon barrier and knock-in levels, the investor continues remaining invested but does not receive the respective month’s interest. If the product is not autocalled during its life cycle and  reaches the scheduled maturity date, there are three possible scenarios to consider: in the first the price is above the autocall barrier, coupon barrier and knock-in level prices (in this case investors receive the principal plus this last month’s interest); in the second, the price is below the autocall level but above the coupon barrier and knock-in level (in this case interest is paid, although the underlying’s return is negative); in the third case, in which the price is below the autocall level, the coupon barrier and the knock-in level (in this worst case 


                  Autocall structured products  83                            scenario the investor is exposed fully to the downside as the company is has bought a put option). 4  Database and methodology This chapter was divided into two sections. The first part describes the database used in the treatment of information and the second part presents the methodology used for the calculations that formed the basis for this study’s results. 4.1 Database The database was obtained from two distinct sources: Bloomberg, according to the  data entry parameters described by Citigroup Funding Inc. in the issue contract of this Vale S.A. structured product and ECONOMÁTICA. The entry data in the model are composed of the start price of US$ 34.50 (obtained from Bloomberg on 03/04/2011) which automatically generated other data such as the autocall (US$ 34.50) knock-in and the coupon barrier (US$ 27.60). The coupon paid (stipulated by contract) is 11% per year which can generate monthly payments of 0.917% if the product’s price is at conditional levels that provide for this payment, as explained above. The main volatility (ơ) of the model is 0.36 (considering historical volatility – obtained from the price database of ECONOMÀTICA), and varies between 0.10 and 1.00 (for experimental modelling) in order to note the pricing discrepancies due to it – which is the only conditional variable that can be manipulated to influence this product’s pricing. 4.2 Methodology The analysis covers the 12-month period from the start price established for Vale S.A. (VALE) stock, on 03/04/2011, so that this product’s data inputs (coupon barrier, knock-in and autocall) begin at this start price. The modifications in the trinomial tree include the coupon barrier, knock-in and autocall conditions, as well as the dynamics of the calculation of the note’s present value taking these conditions into consideration. I should be mentioned that the trinomial tree model proposed is exactly that one of Hull (2006). Changes were only incorporated in the present value calculation and in the inclusion of the conditional coupon barrier knock-in and autocall. The coupon payments, based on the capital invested are brought to present value according to the price’s position in the tree, that is, its position at the node. Thus, one can note that the conditions should be analysed on an individual basis for each tree node. It should also be noted that the underlying asset assumes a geometric Brownian motion. In order to achieve a better understanding an illustrative model is generated in  Figure 7, considering that the product has a maximum life of three months. 


                 84  P.V.J. da Gama Silva et al.                            Figure 7  Demonstration of the calculation of the modified trinomial model  This example considered an initial price (P0) of US$ 34.50, autocall level of US$ 34.50 and coupon barrier and knock-in level of US$ 27.60, and used a volatility of 0.2 (or 20%). The underlined values show the coupon payments due according to the Vale S.A. product’s conditions and the values in bold-type refer to the present value of the coupon paid. Thus, the value in bold-type noted below the initial price is the product’s final present value (which is the sum of the all other values in bold-type). During the first period, it can be observed that the price of $ 37.44 exceeds the autocall barrier and the price of $ 34.50 attains it and thus they are redeemed and the principal plus interest $ 1,000 * 1.0917 = $ 1,009.17 are rescued, so that the subsequent calculation for this ‘node’ is no longer needed since the product finished in this part of the tree. The present value is then generated as follows: 


                  Autocall structured products  85                            ()()()()()1    121rPV Principal Cumulative probability for each nodenExp Ln r T⎡⎤=×+×⎢⎥⎣⎦⎡⎤×−+×⎣⎦ (13)where r = the coupon amount paid for the product n = the relevant observation period T = the total period. Applying equation (13) the amount paid of $ 1,009.17 * (the probability of rising 0.2950) * Exp [–Ln (1.11) * (1/12)] = $ 295.14. As stated above present values are obtained according to the position of the node, that is, taking as an example the value of US$ 31.80 in the second period, the payment is $ 9.17 ($ 1000 * 0.0917), because the barrier of autocall was not reached (only the interest payments), and thus the calculation of the PV value for this kind of situation will change to: ()()()()()   121rPV Principal Cumulative probability for each nodenExp Ln r T⎡⎤=××⎢⎥⎣⎦⎡⎤×−+×⎣⎦ (14) Applying equation (14) the amount paid of $ 9.17 * (the probability of falling 0.2087 * the probability of remaining stable 0.4963) * Exp [–Ln (1.11) * (2/12)] = $ 0.93. In the example in Figure 7 no price in period 1 and 2 was below the barrier coupon payment of $ 27.60. Should this occur, the interest payment would be zero and the calculation of the product would continue to be done. Period three, in this illustrative example, has the same conditional as period 12. Thus, it is clear that if the price closes above the barrier during the last period, the investor obtains the principal plus interest and if it closes below the coupon barrier Vale S.A is in fact buying a put option and the buyer is short – the calculation is:  0     TPrincipalClosing Below the Coupon Barrier PP⎛⎞=×⎜⎟⎝⎠ (15) Appling the equation (15) (1,000 / 34.50) * 27.00 = 782.62. In order to automate the calculation process a calculation methodology was developed that seeks to exploit the product’s conditionals with the matrix idea for the work with the database (using the computer language VBA in Excel). The Vale S.A. prices used to calculate historical volatility were obtained on a daily basis during the 12 months prior to the issue of the note, from the ECONOMATICA database. They were adjusted for dividends but not for inflation (a value of 0.36 or 36% was found). Historical volatility, according to, da Silva (2008), corresponds to the standard deviation of the natural logarithms of the between consecutive periods. It iscalculated as follows: 


                 86  P.V.J. da Gama Silva et al.                            1 Calculatel n (Pi / Pi–1) for each period, where Pi is the closing price of period i and Pi–1 is the same closing price of the previous period. 2  Calculate the standard deviation of the values calculated in item 1 for the n periods that precede the period considered (n is a parameter of the indicator). 3  Annualise the volatility obtained in item 2. For example, if the values of item 1 are on a daily basis, multiply the standard deviation of item 2 by the square root of 252 (where 252 = the approximate number of business days in a year). Some pricing scenarios will be structured using volatility as the basis for the analysis of the product during this period. 5 Results Through a structured analysis, as can be seen in Table 5, the research developed scenarios considering different maturities of 1 to 12 months for the Vale S.A. product, as well as a volatility that varied from 0.1 to 1 (also considering a historical volatility of 0.36). Table 5  Analysis of scenarios considering different maturities impacted by volatility Price at zero date (US$) Maturity (in months) Volatility (ơ) 1 2 3 4 5 6 0.1  $1,000.43 $1,000.50 $1,000.54 $1,000.57 $1,000.59 $1,000.61 0.2 $1,000.43 $1,000.52 $998.57 $997.06 $996.01 $995.28 0.3 $1,000.43 $988.74 $984.69 $982.83 $981.85 $981.27 0.36 $1,000.43 $985.74 $980.58 $978.17 $976.86 $976.08 0.4 $1,000.43 $983.72 $977.82 $975.04 $973.52 $972.61 0.5 $1,000.43 $978.67 $970.88 $967.17 $965.12 $963.86 0.6 $941.40 $941.96 $942.24 $942.41 $942.53 $942.62 0.7 $931.22 $931.78 $932.06 $932.23 $932.35 $932.44 0.8 $921.06 $921.62 $921.89 $922.06 $922.18 $922.27 0.9 $910.91 $911.47 $911.75 $911.92 $912.03 $912.12 1  $900.79 $901.35 $901.62 $901.79 $901.90 $901.99   7 8 9 10 11 12 0.1  $1,000.62 $1,000.62 $1,000.62 $1,000.62 $1,000.62 $1,000.61 0.2 $994.76 $994.40 $994.13 $993.94 $993.80 $993.70 0.3 $980.91 $980.68 $980.53 $980.43 $980.37 $980.32 0.36 $975.59 $975.27 $975.04 $974.89 $974.78 $974.70 0.4 $972.02 $971.63 $971.36 $971.17 $971.03 $970.92 0.5 $963.04 $962.48 $962.09 $961.80 $961.59 $961.43 0.6 $942.69 $942.74 $942.79 $942.83 $942.86 $942.89 0.7 $932.50 $932.58 $932.60 $932.64 $932.68 $932.70 0.8 $922.34 $922.39 $922.44 $922.47 $922.51 $922.53 0.9 $912.19 $912.24 $912.29 $912.32 $912.35 $912.38 1  $902.06 $902.11 $902.15 $902.19 $902.22 $902.25 Source: Own calculus 


                  Autocall structured products  87                            The Table 6 shows the price in the 12-month maturity scenario (which is the baseline scenario considering the total expected duration) with a volatility of 0.1, 0.36 and 1. Table 6  Analysis considering start and end interval of the volatility and the historical volatility Input data for evaluate  the product of Vale S.A.   Input data for evaluate  the product of Vale S.A. Input data for evaluate  the product of Vale S.A. Strike price  $34.50    Strike price $34.50  Strike Price $34.50 Autocall $34.50  Autocall $34.50  Autocall $34.50 Barrier $27.60  Barrier $27.60  Barrier $27.60 Knock-in $27.60  Knock-in $27.60  Knock-in $27.60 Coupon  11% a.a.    Coupon  11% a.a.  Coupon  11% a.a. Maturity 12 months  Maturity 12 months  Maturity  12 months Frequency Per month  Frequency Per month  Frequency  Per month Volatility 0.10  Volatility 0.36  Volatility 1.00 Data generated by the model    Data generated by the model  Data generated by the model u 1.0417  U 1.1583  u 1.5042 d 0.9600  d 0.8633  d 0.6648 m 1.0000  m 1.0000  m 1.0000 Pu 0.3620  Pu 0.2614  Pu 0.2114 Pd 0.1587  Pd 0.2389  Pd 0.2919 Pm 0.4793  Pm 0.4997  Pm 0.4968 Product price at zero date    Product price at zero date  Product price at zero date $1,000.61   $974.70  $902.25 Source: Own calculus The scenarios with the highest prices on the initial date may be observed in an environment of lower volatility, of 10%, which is quite rare in this type of industry (but more likely in the power sector, for example). Moreover, the highest price of all the simulations – US$ 1,000.62 – occurs in this same volatility scenario from the seventh to the tenth period. It is important to note that the increase in volatility leads to a significant decline in prices (with the lowest – US$ 900.79 – found in the scenario of 100% volatility during the first period. During the first period it can be observed that there is a greater degree of ‘indifference’ in pricing due to the variation of volatility (in the cases of volatilities of 10% to 50% prices remain constant at US$ 1,000.43). The margin of price variation, considering their deviation by period, is greater at the first redemption than at the others, with the lowest being during the last period, as prices are then declining. It can also be observed that with very low volatility of say 10% and high volatility of 60% to 100%, the price of the longer maturity note is greater than one with a shorter duration. The contrary occurs when volatility is between 20% and 50%. Therefore, the ideal for autocall structured products is precisely a short maturity (with redemption occurring during the first months of the product’s life) in an environment of moderate volatility so that an investor can seek similar products and obtain a profit. 


                 88  P.V.J. da Gama Silva et al.                            Figure 8 shows the actual behaviour of the coupon barrier note issued by Vale S.A. Figure 8  Real product pricing considering the validation dates and realised periods  Source: Own calculus Observing the product’s actual behaviour, it can be seen that investors incurred losses, in as much as: the product completed its lifecycle, had coupon non-payment dates and on the final date the price was below the barrier and the knock-in level – which led to a greater exposure on the part of investors who faced a loss of 31% at the end. As regards the pricing of the product, in as much as price volatility during the period attained  40%, considering  daily prices in dollars from 03/04/11 to 03/19/12, as well as dividends) in the scenarios cited in Table 5, the product has a present value of  US$ 970.92. 6 Conclusions This study sought to describe various features of the autocall structure in complex products which involve differentiated methodologies due to various details of calculation (as mentioned above in the typology of this product) in an appropriate pricing model. As seen above, volatility, due to autocall, influences the pricing of these products in a very peculiar fashion – which, according to the interval analysed for the total life of the product (12 months) varies between US$ 1,000.61 and US$ 902.25. Thus, one may note that volatility acts as the main measure of dispersion of the product’s returns. It was observed in this study that the use of a reliable model to price autocall products that is concerned with being agile enough to process large databases in order to maintain the data accuracy necessary to ensure the adequate functioning of these structured products, enables investors to assess whether the product’s return (according to its historic volatility) is over or underestimated. Therefore, based on the information collected or scenarios developed, investors will be able to undertake their operations (which may be hedging, arbitrage or speculative 


                  Autocall structured products  89                            operations – depending on the type of product). Thus, it is necessary to calibrate models to the reality of the market in which they will be used and to product typology. References Alexander, C. and Sheedy, E. (2007) The Professional Risk Managers' Guide to Financial Instruments, 1st ed., PRMIA, New York. Ames, W.F. (1977) Numerical Methods for Partial Differential Equation, 2nd ed., Academic Press, New York. Anderson, D., Pletcher, R. and Tannehill, J.C. (1997) Computational Fluid Mechanics and Heat Transfer, 2nd ed., Taylor & Francis, Philadelphia. Baule, R., Entrop, O. and Wilkens, M. (2008) ‘Credit risk and bank margins in structured financial products: evidence from the German secondary market for discount certificates’, Journal of Futures Markets, Vol. 28, No. 4, pp.376–397. Bergstresser, B.D. (2008) The Retail Market for Structured Notes: Insurance Patterns and Performance, Working Paper [02163], Harvard Business School, Harvard University, Boston. Bloomberg [online] http://www.bloomberg.com (accessed 11 February 2010). Bouzoubaa, M. and Osseiran, A. (2010) Exotic Options and Hybrids: A Guide to Structuring, Pricing and Trading, 1st ed., John Wiley & Sons, West Sussex, UK. Boyle, P. (1986) ‘Option valuation using a three-jump process’, International Options Journal, Vol. 3, No. 1, pp.7–12. CitiFirst (2011) Designation of Citigroup’s family of investment strategies 1 [online] https://www.citifirst.com/PT/default.aspx?force=PT (accessed 22 August 2011). Collatz, L. (1966) The Numerical Treatment of Differential Equations, 3rd ed., Springer-Verlag, Berlin. Cox, J., Ross, S. and Rubinstein, M. (1979) ‘Option pricing: a simplified approach’, Journal of Financial Economics, Vol. 7, No. 3, pp.229–263. da Silva, L.M. (2008) Mercado de Opções – Conceitos e Estratégias, 3rd ed., Halip, Rio de Janeiro, BR. Deng, G., Guedj, I., Mallet, J. and McCann, C. (2010) ‘The anatomy of absolute return b